It is an unequal combat when one man defends his cause with head and
heart, the other with head alone. The first has sun and wind against
him, as it were, and his two weapons interfere with each other: he loses
the prize—in the eyes of truth. True, the victory of the second, with
his one weapon, is seldom a victory after the hearts of all the other
spectators, and makes him unpopular.
