The period of life in which a philosopher finds his teaching is manifested
by his teaching; he cannot avoid that, however elevated above time and
hour he may feel himself. Thus, Schopenhauer’s philosophy remains a
mirror of his hot and melancholy youth—it is no mode of thought for
older men. Plato’s philosophy reminds one of the middle thirties,
when a warm and a cold current generally rush together, so that spray
and delicate clouds and, under favourable circumstances and glimpses of
sunshine, enchanting rainbow-pictures result.
